# gen28: quantities as knowledge — assert, recall, and compare magnitudes that
# live in the KB (quantity(entity, unit, value)). This lifts gen27's literal
# comparator into a fact-driven one: the comparison can now be *stated in
# language* rather than handed two raw numbers.
#
# The shape mirrors BoolQ #0 ("does ethanol take more energy than it produces"),
# reduced to its two extracted quantities — energy input vs energy output. We
# test the reasoning over stated quantities; prose->facts extraction is not yet
# built (see Decisions D-2026-06-15a).
> input has 1 energy
< Learned: input has 1 energy.
> output has 1.3 energy
< Learned: output has 1.3 energy.
> how many energy does output have?
< output has 1.3 energy.
# The BoolQ verdict, reached by comparing stated quantities: input < output.
> does input have more energy than output?
< No.
> does output have more energy than input?
< Yes.
> does input have less energy than output?
< Yes.
# A missing quantity is admitted, never invented.
> does input have more energy than rival?
< I don't know how many energy rival has.
> how many energy does rival have?
< I don't know how many energy rival has.
# Non-quantity "has" statements are declined here and fall through.
> alice has a cat
< I don't understand that yet.